  "text": "Viruses of the family Geminiviridae are small singlestranded DNA (ssDNA) phytopathogens encapsidated within geminate particles. They are divided into four genera based on their genome organization, host range and insect vector, with the genus Begomovirus being the largest Rojas et al., 2005; Brown et al., 2011) . Begomoviruses cause numerous diseases of economically important dicotyledonous crops across the world [CITATION_1] . The genomes of some begomoviruses consist of two DNA molecules, referred to as DNA A and DNA B, each of about 2.8 kb. However, across the Old World, most have genomes that consist of a single component (Brown et al., 2011) .",
